^["stream"]{
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] observe - The current Pretext page is an observatory, not yet a whimsy lab: one prepared handle, three width projections, and a small telemetry panel grounded in `prepareWithSegments` plus `layoutWithLines`.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] observe - The bridge in `pretext-utils.js` is intentionally thin and CDN-backed, which means any whimsy plan has to preserve explicit offline/error states instead of assuming the engine is always present.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] observe - What Pretext truthfully exposes here is line text, per-line width, total line count, total height, and multilingual wrapping behavior; it does not expose glyph outlines or arbitrary motion primitives.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] decide - Keep whimsy in a bounded experimental lane on the Pretext page rather than dissolving it across the whole site.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] decide - Treat SVG as a likely rendering partner, but keep the capability note honest enough that experiments could also render in HTML where that is simpler.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:06] taste - The delight here should feel like text unexpectedly learning new postures while still telling the truth about its own layout.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:29] decide - The whimsy lab should lean further into physics: line boxes become inspectable bodies under explicit constraints rather than just playful projections.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:29] revise - Physics here means deterministic force profiles seeded by width, line count, height, order, and anchors; it does not mean a generic particle engine detached from the text.
 >>[2026-04-09 21:29] taste - The right feeling is weight, tension, settling, orbit, or compression made legible enough to inspect, not decorative chaos.
 >>[2026-04-09 23:45] maintain - Added `css-progressive-ornaments` as the CSS boundary plan for whimsy, physics, and seasonal ornament styling so Pretext experiments do not leak into the global stylesheet.
 >>[2026-04-09] style - The lab has the best opportunity of any surface to make the site's metaphysics felt rather than merely read. Boon/bane, charge, pivot, and spirit phase already have physical analogues waiting in the site's semantic grammar. The first physics profiles should translate those, not invent generic forces with coincidentally similar names.
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - Candidate translations already present in the vocabulary: boon field → gentle gravity drawing lines toward a common anchor; bane pressure → distributing force that pushes overloaded lines outward; charge accumulation → progressive offset scaling by line order or dwell depth; pivot → sudden structural reorientation around a measured line's axis; spirit phase → ambient attractor that biases the overall field without eliminating alternatives.
 >>[2026-04-09] style - The signature delight quality on this site should feel like text learning its own weight — settling, orienting, responding to attention — rather than performing physics as spectacle. The difference between those two is whether the force is seeded by measurement or by aesthetic caprice.
}

^["open"]{
 ?[capabilities]: "Which experiment families are honest consequences of line widths, line count, height, order, anchors, and mixed-script handling rather than generic animation?"
 ?[physics]: "Which force families are honest enough to feel physical while still being inspectable from the line metrics Pretext actually returns?"
 ?[teaching]: "What is the right ladder from observatory to whimsy so the page stays explanatory before it becomes playful?"
 ?[rendering]: "Which whimsical projections should be SVG-backed, which should remain HTML, and where is that distinction worth the complexity?"
 ?[mobile]: "How should experiment selection and projection switching collapse on phones without turning the lab into a panel maze?"
 ?[telemetry]: "What metrics or labels must stay visible so a user can tell what the experiment is actually measuring?"
 ?[symmetry]: "How should keyboard and touch choose experiments and local pivots while writing the same projection state?"
 ?[fallback]: "What is the graceful degradation path when the CDN import fails or a whimsical projection is disabled?"
 ?[reuse]: "Which whimsy patterns are likely to generalize into later widgets or Spw-backed pages?"
 ?[spw_physics_seeds]: "Which operator semantics should seed the first physics profiles — boon/gravity, bane/pressure, pivot/reorientation, charge/offset, spirit-phase/ambient-attractor — and how does each map to a measurable line constraint?"
 ?[metaphysics_legibility]: "Should experiments name their Spw metaphysical nature explicitly (boon-field, bane-pressure) or let the behavior speak first and allow naming to follow from inspection?"
 ?[delight_fingerprint]: "What is the signature feeling of delight specific to this site — settling, orienting, weighing, orbiting, or something the existing copy and operator pages already imply?"
 ?[personal_emergence]: "At which commit should the first physics profile's metaphysical source be logged as a taste decision, not an incidental implementation choice?"
}

^["commits"]{
 ~[1]: "#[pretext] - capture the whimsy lab plan and distilled capability lattice"
 ~[2]: ".[pretext] - formalize whimsy doctrine, physics profiles, experiment boundaries, and truthful telemetry rules"
 ~[3]: "&[pretext] - split the observatory runtime from the whimsy experiment runtime"
 ~[4]: "&[physics] - add first layout-driven physical projections and inspect surfaces"
 ~[5]: "![pretext] - verify touch, responsiveness, offline degradation, and telemetry honesty"
}

